Lamb is not my favorite thing, but this stew is delicious, worth the trouble of the trimming of five pounds of lamb chops. Probably the bones add a lot of the richness to the finished product. Served over mashed potatoes--excellent.

Rating: 4
I hadn't made this recipe in a couple of years but decided it was just the thing for my book group meeting. I picked the book "The Banished Children of Eve" by Peter Quinn for our March selection, as it had to do with the Irish immigrants in this country during the Civil War. I then decided to do an Irish dinner theme and knew this Irish Stew recipe would be perfect. Yes, it does require a considerable amount of prep time but is well worth the effort. I did find that the fat rendering took more that five minutes. I used my largest LeCrueset roasting pan and did the fat on low for about 20 minutes. Not only do you get enough fat to brown all the meat, but wonderful brown bits in the pan as well. I'm serving Irish cheeses to start, the stew with Irish soda bread and Irish butter, and will finish off the meal with an Irish whiskey cake - a recipe from Downey's here in Philadelphia. Of course, there will be plenty of Irish coffees as well!!!! This recipe is not for the faint hearted, but once you go to the trouble this will be your all time favoite! Enjoy!!

